SIMPLE: stroke
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stroke
<hw>Stroke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <pos>imp.</pos> <mord>of
<er>Strike</er></mord>. <def>Struck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stroke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stroke
<hw>Stroke</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>strok</ets>,
<ets>strook</ets>, <ets>strak</ets>, fr. <ets>striken</ets>. See
<er>Strike</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
striking; a blow; a hit; a knock; esp., a violent or hostile attack made
with the arm or hand, or with an instrument or weapon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His hand fetcheth a <qex>stroke</qex> with the ax to cut down the
tree.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xix. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A fool's lips enter into contention and his mouth calleth for
<qex>strokes</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xviii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He entered and won the whole kingdom of Naples without striking a
<qex>stroke</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The result of effect of a striking; injury or
affliction; soreness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the day that Lord bindeth up the breach of his people, and
healeth the <qex>stroke</qex> of their wound.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xxx.
26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The striking of the clock to tell the
hour.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well, but what's o'clock?⟦br⟧
- Upon the <qex>stroke</qex> of ten. -- Well, let is strike.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A gentle, caressing touch or movement upon
something; a stroking.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A mark or dash in writing or printing; a line; the
touch of a pen or pencil; <as>as, an up <ex>stroke</ex>; a firm
<ex>stroke</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, lasting as those colors may they shine,⟦br⟧
Free as thy <qex>stroke</qex>, yet faultless as thy line.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Hence, by extension, an addition or amandment to a
written composition; a touch; <as>as, to give some finishing
<ex>strokes</ex> to an essay</as>.</def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A sudden attack of disease; especially, a fatal
attack; a severe disaster; any affliction or calamity, especially a
sudden one; <as>as, a <ex>stroke</ex> of apoplexy; the <ex>stroke</ex>
of death</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At this one <qex>stroke</qex> the man looked dead in law.</q>
<rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A throb or beat, as of the heart.</def>
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>One of a series of beats or movements against a
resisting medium, by means of which movement through or upon it is
accomplished; <as>as, the <ex>stroke</ex> of a bird's wing in flying, or
an oar in rowing, of a skater, swimmer, etc.</as></def>; also:
<fld>(Rowing)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The rate of succession of stroke;
<as>as, a quick <ex>stroke</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The oar
nearest the stern of a boat, by which the other oars are guided; --
called also <altname>stroke oar</altname>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The
rower who pulls the stroke oar; the strokesman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A powerful or sudden effort by which something is
done, produced, or accomplished; also, something done or accomplished by
such an effort; <as>as, a <ex>stroke</ex> of genius; a <ex>stroke</ex>
of business; a master <ex>stroke</ex> of policy.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>The movement, in either
direction, of the piston plunger, piston rod, crosshead, etc., as of a
steam engine or a pump, in which these parts have a reciprocating
motion; <as>as, the forward <ex>stroke</ex> of a piston</as>; also, the
entire distance passed through, as by a piston, in such a movement;
<as>as, the piston is at half <ex>stroke</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The respective strokes are distinguished as
<xex>up</xex> and <xex>down</xex> strokes, <xex>outward</xex> and
<xex>inward</xex> strokes, <xex>forward</xex> and <xex>back</xex>
strokes, the forward stroke in stationary steam engines being toward the
crosshead, but in locomotives toward the front of the
vehicle.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>Power; influence.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Where money beareth [hath] all the <xex>stroke</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Robynson (More's Utopia).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He has a great <qex>stroke</qex> with the reader.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>Appetite.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To keep stroke</b></col>, <cd>to make strokes in
unison.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The oars where silver,⟦br⟧
Which to the tune of flutes <qex>kept stroke</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stroke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stroke
<hw>Stroke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Strokeed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Strokeing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stroken</ets>, <ets>straken</ets>, AS. <ets>str⟦amac⟧cian</ets>,
fr. <ets>str⟦imac⟧can</ets> to go over, pass. See <er>Strike</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>, and cf. <er>Straggle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
strike.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye mote with the plat sword again⟦br⟧
<qex>Stroken</qex> him in the wound, and it will close.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rib gently in one direction; especially, to pass
the hand gently over by way of expressing kindness or tenderness; to
caress; to soothe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He dried the falling drops, and, yet more kind,⟦br⟧
He <qex>stroked</qex> her cheeks.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make smooth by rubbing.</def>
<rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Masonry)</fld> <def>To give a finely fluted surface
to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To row the stroke oar of; <as>as, to <ex>stroke</ex>
a boat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stroker</ent>⟦br⟧
